Explorium is an external data platform providing data services to businesses about businesses. The Explorium platform and services assist marketing and sales teams with tailored go-to market data, allow predictive prospecting, lead scoring, supply chain analysis and enrichment of customer's databases. As such, we may process any of the following categories of data about business and professionals.  

* Identifiers and other  information such as name, signature, address, unique personal identifier, online identifier, IP address, email address, telephone number. 
* Commercial information, including records products, or services purchased, obtained, or considered, or other purchasing or consuming histories or tendencies.
* Internet or other similar network activity and technical information related to use of mobile device or computer.
* Professional or employment-related information, such as employment history, skills certifications, or job titles.
* Inferences drawn from other personal information, such as preferences, characteristics, behavior, and aptitudes in capacity of business activities. 

Explorium never shares  with any third party data which our customers provide to us in order to use our platform and services, and we never share any of our platform usage data.

column66: By the nature of our business, completing a request in part is not applicable, as all valid requests are either fully processed or rejected with an explanation for invalid or noncompliant submissions.

*For questions 37-42, LiveRamp processes a “request to know what personal information was sold or shared” as a “request to access” a consumer’s personal information.
*For questions 49-54, LiveRamp processes a “request to limit the use and disclosure of sensitive personal information” as a “request to opt-out”.

column67: The MarketOps system adheres to strict data minimization and privacy protection protocols in accordance with current regulatory requirements. We process only anonymized consumer interactions that are specifically relevant to each client's business operations, following established data privacy frameworks. The platform aggregates anonymized browsing signals into statistical trends, maintaining user privacy while providing market insights. All data collection and processing follows privacy-by-design principles, including data minimization, purpose limitation, and strict anonymization protocols. Our privacy-centric architecture ensures regulatory compliance while enabling clients to access aggregated market intelligence. The system employs multiple technical safeguards to maintain user anonymity throughout data processing and analysis workflows, with no ability to re-identify individual users. We maintain comprehensive documentation of our privacy protection measures and regularly review our processes to ensure alignment with evolving privacy regulations and industry standards.

ACH takes all necessary steps to ensure that the data we collect, license, and process is housed and transmitted securely.  ACH adheres to all federal and state privacy laws, as well as self-regulatory industry principles.
ACH follows industry standards on information security management to safeguard personal information which includes physical and electronic security, including, but not limited to firewall protections and encryption.
Personal information is collected from processing centers for the purposes of marketing, and analysis. 
The information collected by ACH is done so in accordance with client’s privacy policy.
The data collected from Personal Information is defined as any information concerning the personal or material circumstances of an identified or identifiable individual. Personal Information shall include but is not limited to: name, home address, home zip code, home telephone number, mobile phone number, or email address.
ACH does not collect sensitive data concerning a consumer, i.e. health data, political and philosophical beliefs, precise geolocation, racial/ ethnic data.
ACH does not knowingly collect personal information from anyone under the age of 18.
Personal Information is not accessible to anyone outside the specific function for which it is collected.
ACH does not use affiliates or unauthorized third party data.
ACH works on an “As-Is” basis without warranties of any kind.
ACH will keep personal information as long as necessary for our business purposes, as described in this Privacy Policy. Once personal information is no longer needed, it will be removed from our system.

column67: We are a marketing company whose clients range from some of the biggest companies and charities in the U.S. to local charities, such as food banks. We help our clients identify people who might be interested in their marketing offers. Sometimes our research is intended to help our clients find new donors or customers, others to find new ways to serve or connect with existing donors or customers. But whether they are our clients, the American consumer, or others, we care about people, and provide consumers with privacy choices. We have provided a form and a toll free number on our website at www.Wiland.com/privacy-choices for consumers to submit requests under the CCPA.  We believe in honoring consumers' privacy choices, as described above. We do not currently make consumer information publicly available via a website or other online service, nor do we currently host public websites where other consumers could post this information.   Please see www.Wiland.com/Privacy-Choices for more information about our products and services, how we use and protect consumer personal information and how consumers can exercise their privacy choices.  We use consumer data for the purpose of creating products and services intended to help consumers receive relevant marketing offers and to reduce marketing waste and unwanted advertising. We require our clients to use our products only for marketing related activities, and not for sensitive decisions like credit, employment or housing. In addition, we limit the type of data we receive and the type of data we share in the interest of consumer privacy. We don't possess or utilize sensitive data like credit card or bank account numbers, Social Security Numbers or other government-issued identifiers. We do not accept or generate information specifying individuals' health conditions (such as protected health information, aka "HIPAA data"). We don't release information to third parties concerning specific items that a consumer has purchased, what magazines they read, or what charities they support unless requested by the organization with whom the consumer has a relationship.  Our marketing products and services are designed only for use in marketing to United States consumers above the age of 18. We do not knowingly collect information about consumers residing in other locations (such as Europe) or about children.  We seek to work only with reputable organizations.  After all, we are consumers too, and care deeply how consumer data is used.  We have a documented client approval process that is reviewed and updated periodically. We don’t work with clients whose product or service we believe to be illegal, fraudulent, pornographic or harmful to families.  Executive officer approval is required for accepting an engagement with a new client.  We belong to several industry groups such as the Data and Marketing Association division of the ANA and the Digital Advertising Alliance. One reason these self-regulatory groups exist is to ensure that companies commit to honoring consumer choice. In addition to the privacy choices we offer consumers directly, we encourage consumers to utilize industry solutions, such as the DMA mail and email preference services and the DAA Ad Choices service to cast a broader net for their advertising choices.  The DMA consumer choice website is: https://dmachoice.org/.  The DAA consumer choice website is: http://youradchoices.com.

Spokeo has since January 1, 2023 regarded the information it sells as "publicly available information" as defined by the California Consumer Privacy Act (excluding information subject to the GLBA that Spokeo collects and sells via its RPC product, as explained elsewhere in this registration).  Nevertheless, as Spokeo voluntarily done for many years, Spokeo allows consumers to opt out of the sale of "publicly available information" from its public websites.  In this section, Spokeo is reporting the metrics associated with consumers' requests to opt out of the sale of "publicly available information" from its public websites.  The reported metrics associated with consumers' requests to opt out of the sale of "publicly available information" from its public websites in 2023 aggregates the number of requests received through the Thatsthem.com website and through the Spokeo website.  

Spokeo aggregates the number of requests complied with in whole or in part.

All requests submitted in accordance with the instructions provided in the privacy policies posted on the Spokeo and Thatsthem.com websites are processed in real time following completion of the request submittal.

Spokeo does not use or disclose sensitive personal information.
column67:
The information sold by Spokeo consists of "publicly available information" as defined by the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), which is excluded from the definition of "personal information" and subject to First Amendment protections for free speech, and information subject to the GLBA to which the CCPA does not apply.  

Nevertheless, Spokeo elects to be included in this registry to inform CA residents about the nature of the publicly available information that Spokeo provides on its public websites and how to opt-out.

The categories of publicly available information that are available on Spokeo’s websites are described in Spokeo's Privacy Policy located at https://www.spokeo.com/privacy-policy and in the "Where does Spokeo's profile data come from?" section on this webpage: https://www.spokeo.com/privacy/control/all-categories.

Spokeo enables all consumers, including CA residents, to opt out from having their publicly available information available on Spokeo's public websites. Consumers may complete their opt out request online by using our self-help tool located at https://www.spokeo.com/optout.  As of the writing of this registration, an opt out completed from this page will opt a consumer out from all public Spokeo websites except Thatsthem.com.  To opt out from having their publicly available information available on Thatsthem.com, consumers may submit their opt out request at https://www.thatsthem.com/optout.

Consumers may also submit their opt-out request by contacting Spokeo Customer Care via any of the contact methods listed at https://www.spokeo.com/contact (which includes a nationwide toll free number).  Spokeo's Customer Care agents will gladly assist consumers with completing an opt out request for all of Spokeo's public websites.

Snovio receives and processes Data subject access requests (DSAR) which are formal inquiries made by individuals to a company. It involves the data subject seeking information regarding collecting, storing, and using their personal data. Any individual who qualifies as a data subject can submit such a request.

We cannot measure the volume of personal data processed in such requests; we can only ensure its deletion upon request. Users can request that the company delete all the data associated with them, a right commonly referred to as the right to erasure or the right to be forgotten.

Snovio only collects specific categories of data that are essential to providing our services. This includes:

Email Addresses: For identifying individuals within our platform.
Names: To provide personalized results and accurate matching.
Company Information: Such as company name, position, and industry for professional networking purposes.
Publicly Available Information: From open sources, such as websites or social profiles, used in compliance with applicable privacy laws.
Snovio does not collect sensitive personal data unless explicitly provided by the user for service-related purposes.

How Can Users Request Data Deletion?
To request the deletion of their data, users can either:

Contact us directly by sending an email to help@snov.io.
Fill out the online form https://app.snov.io/clear-email 
opt-out narrative:
If you do not want your personal data to be included as part of our service, you may opt-out by contacting us at help@snov.io or opt-out from all mailing lists on the Platform through this form. You can read more in the ‘HOW TO DELETE MY DATA’ section of this Policy.
, which provides an automated way to manage their request.
What Can Users Request?
A summary of the information the company stores about them.
Details on whether anyone has had access to their data.
Deletion of all personal data from the system.
We are committed to processing these requests promptly and in full compliance with applicable data privacy regulations.

The number of requests is generally high as we do not differentiate between California residents and residents of other states or countries when respecting and responding to privacy requests, and as such can only provide the total number of requests we receive which include residents of other states and countries. We stop processing and any onward transfers based on either election.

column22: The service of acting as a "finder". See 16 CFR § 314.3(h)(1): Financial institution means any institution the business of which is engaging in an activity that is financial in nature or incidental to such financial activities as described in section 4(k) of the Bank Holding Company Act of 1956, 12 U.S.C. 1843(k). An institution that is significantly engaged in financial activities, or significantly engaged in activities incidental to such financial activities, is a financial institution. Then at (h)(2)(xiii): A company acting as a finder in bringing together one or more buyers and sellers of any product or service for transactions that the parties themselves negotiate and consummate is a financial institution because acting as a finder is an activity that is financial in nature or incidental to a financial activity listed in 12 CFR 225.86(d)(1).

column67: I honestly don't think we need to register under the CA law as a Data Broker... but I am doing this out of an abundance of just-in-case mentality. We are a publishing and media company.  We had total revenue of $14.1 million dollars in 2024.  Of that, we generated a total of $564,200 from payments made to us by third party advertisers to access our data as we approved.  That amounts to 4% of our revenue.  For whatever it’s worth, in 2023 we received 0 consumer requests regarding data.  In 2024 we received 77 consumer requests to exercise their CCPA rights.  While we added all 77 of those individuals to our global opt-out file so that they could not ever receive our messages going forward, not a single one of them even existed in our data prior to their request.  Not one. Since we send emails and texts to our customers (and never physical mail or the like), we lack information on the actual residency of our customers — unless they tell us that information in a CCPA rights request for instance.  Under all the regulations from the CPPA link below, I doubt very much that we should ever have registered as a CA Data Broker in the first place.  But in case we might have 100,000 CA residents in our data and not know it, I have decided to continue the registration.

When we get an opt-out request from an individual, we delete all of the individual’s data and therefore have not distinguished between these request types. 


The following requests do NOT form part of our reporting:
 1.  LoopMe provides Consumers the ability to opt out of any “sales” or “shares” of their personal data via a web cookie-based opt out tool and a Device ID opt out tool. When a Consumer uses these tools, LoopMe deletes the identifier that we otherwise use to engage in these practices. In line with our data minimization policies, we did not record how many people exercised this choice in the previous calendar year. In light of new legal requirements, LoopMe is now working to include this additional reporting. 
2. Incomplete Requests: We can only process requests where we have all of the required information. For example, we cannot action requests if only the name and/or email of an individual are provided because we do not process that data. In each such case, we responded to the requestor asking for further information required to process the request, and could only process such request where the required additional information was provided.

PureCars customers are auto dealerships that are regulated by the GLBA. For these customers, PureCars offers the following products and services: TruPayments, The AutoMiner, and PureIdentity. PureCars receives NPI from its dealership customers, including from leasing transactions. 

PureCars separates the AutoMiner and PureIdentity business lines’ technical environment from its TruPayments business line’s technical environment. 

For all of its business lines, dealerships have their own tenants that are logically separated. For its targeted advertising service, PureCars will combine a single dealership’s NPI with additional sources of personal information, such as from data brokers, which PureCars shares with third-party platforms, such as Google or Meta. PureCars does not share customer data with other customers.

BDO’s Global Corporate Intelligence services were previously registered as part of BDO USA, P.C., which is no longer a data broker under California law. BDO GCI, LLC was recently formed, and did not receive any data subject requests in 2023. 

For the period beginning on January 1, 2023, and ending on December 31, 2023, BDO has compiled the following statistics regarding individual requests to know, access, delete, and opt out of sale, sharing and/or targeted advertising: BDO received 13,172 total requests, complied with 13,122 of these requests in whole or in part, denied 50 requests, and responded to these requests with a median response timeline of 0 days and a mean of 0.2 days. 

Of these requests, 1 deletion request involved data that BDO USA did not delete pursuant to exceptions under Sections 1798.145 or 1798.146 of the California Consumer Privacy Act of 2018. For this request, BDO USA relied on the exceptions covering our ability to “comply with federal, state, or local laws,” “comply with a civil, criminal, or regulatory inquiry, investigation, subpoena, or summons by federal, state, or local authorities,” and “exercise or defend legal claims.” 

Please note that the number of “Denied” requests includes abandoned requests by the consumer and failed identity verification attempts.

Additionally, please note that these metrics include requests we received at the end of 2023 and responded to in 2024.

BDO USA, P.C. does not sell any personal information obtained in the course of providing Tax, Audit & Assurance, and other Advisory services to its clients. BDO GCI, LLC is retained by its clients to research and provide personal information about individuals in the form of reports as part of investment, transactional, and other due diligence. This practice may amount to a “sale” of personal information as such term is defined under the CCPA. 

To be clear, BDO GCI, LLC does not perform its research services on minors under 16, though it may sometimes collect information about an individual’s children in the course of researching that individual (e.g., if such information is available in news articles or other public sources about the individual).

column66:
Buyerlink Inc. remains committed to compliance with data privacy and security laws and regulations while continuously enhancing its data request processing procedures. 

In the reporting period, we faced significant challenges that contributed to some delays beyond the standard response timeframe. One of the primary issues was a substantial influx of fraudulent or invalid requests, including automated mass privacy requests, submissions from individuals who could not be verified as eligible consumers, and submissions that were general or irrelevant communications unrelated to consumer privacy rights which still required significant manual review to confirm their invalidity. 	

To prevent unauthorized disclosure of sensitive information, each request required extensive manual verification, significantly increasing processing time. Buyerlink utilizes OneTrust, a robust compliance platform, to manage and streamline privacy requests. While the verification of mass invalid requests continues to require substantial time and resources, our 2024 data subject request handling has significantly improved.

column66:
AutoWeb is continuously enhancing its data collection and management processes to address challenges such as mass fraudulent privacy requests, which create unnecessary burdens on company resources.

While we utilize a robust compliance platform, such as OneTrust, to manage privacy requests efficiently, we occasionally encounter high volumes of invalid or fraudulent requests. Verifying and identifying these invalid submissions requires significant time and resources. To mitigate this issue, we are actively refining our processes and implementing additional safeguards to ensure that only legitimate privacy requests are processed while maintaining compliance with applicable regulations.

column67: SpyCloud recovers information stolen from other organizations that is made available by threat actors on the dark web. We refer to this information as "breach data" and it powers our automated identity threat protection solutions that protect our enterprise clients. Our focus is making stolen data actionable to protect businesses from cyberattacks and safeguard employee and consumer identities by alerting them that their information is being shared on the dark web by cybercriminals. Customers globally – including more than half of the Fortune 10 – count on SpyCloud to thwart identity-based attacks including ransomware, account takeover, session hijacking, and online fraud. Our mission is to make the internet safer with automated solutions that help businesses disrupt cybercrime. Together with our customers and partners, we aim to end criminals’ ability to profit from stolen information.
